Classes¶

Classes have been used from the beginning of this course. Most important thing to understand about a class is that it defines a new data type. A class is a template or a blueprint from which objects are made. The great example of a class is a cookie cutter. Cookies are objects themselves. When you counstruct an object from a class you created an instance of a class. When you define a class, you declare its exact form and nature. You do this by specifying the data that it contains and the code that operates on that data. While very simple classes may contain only code or only data, most real-world classes contain both. As you will see, a class’ code defines the interface to its data.

As you may have noticed we always use classes to create even the simplest java application. A class is declared by use of the class keyword.

The data, or variables, defined within a class are called instance variables. The code is contained within methods. Collectively, the methods and variables defined within a class are called members of the class. In most classes, the instance variables are acted upon and accessed by the methods defined for that class. Thus, as a general rule, it is the methods that determine how a class’ data can be used. Variables defined within a class are called instance variables because each instance of the class (that is, each object of the class) contains its own copy of these variables.

All methods have the same general form as main( ), which we have been using thus far. However, most methods will not be specified as static or public. Notice that the general form of a class does not specify a main( ) method. Java classes do not need to have a main( )method. You only specify one if that class is the starting point for your program. Further, some kinds of Java applications don’t require a main( ) method at all.

Defining your own classes¶

Lets create a simple Java class:

In [3]:
public class Box {
    double width;
    double height;
    double depth;
}

As was mentioned before, class defines a new type of data. Is this case we created a new type called Box which represents real world object. Its important to understand that class only creates a template. It doesn't create an actual object. To actually create a box object we need to use the following syntax:

In [2]:
Box aBox = new Box();

After this statement executes, a new Box object will be created and the variable aBox will refere to that object in the memory. Thus, it will have “physical” reality.

In [3]:
System.out.println(aBox);

REPL.$JShell$12$Box@277c6848

As mentioned earlier, each time you create an instance of a class, you are creating an object that contains its own copy of each instance variable defined by the class. Thus, every Box object will contain its own copies of the instance variables width, height, and depth. To access these variables, you will use the dot (.) operator. The dot operator links the name of the object with the name of an instance variable.

In [5]:
aBox.width = 100;
aBox.height = 200;
System.out.println(aBox.width);
System.out.println(aBox.height);

100.0
200.0

Let's create a simple useful programm to calculate the volume of a box by it's parameters.

In [4]:
class BoxDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box myBox = new Box();
        double vol;
        
        myBox.height = 10;
        myBox.width = 12;
        myBox.depth = 10;
        
        // Compute the volume of the box
        vol = myBox.width * myBox.height * myBox.depth;
        System.out.println("Volume is " + vol);
    }
}
In [5]:
BoxDemo.main(new String[]{});

Volume is 1200.0

Encaplulation intro¶

Encapsulation(sometimes called information hiding) is a key concept in working with objects. Formally, encapsulation is a simple combining data and behavior in one package and hiding the implementation details from the users of an object. The key to making encapsulation work is not to allowed users to directly access instance fields in a class. Users should interact with object only via a public interface. The encapsulation is a way to give an object a "Black Box" behavior, which is key for reuse and reliability.

Objects¶

To work with OOP, you should be able to identify three key concepts of objects:

  1. The object's behavior - what can you do with object or what methods can you apply to it.
  2. The object's state - how does the object react when you invoke those methods?
  3. The object's identity - how is the object distinguished from other that may have the same behavior and state

All objects that are instances of the same class share the same behavior. The behavior of an object is defined by the methods that you can call. Each object store the information what it currently looks like. This is the objects state. Object state can be change during time but not spontaneously. A change in object's state must be a result of methods calls.

Relationships between classes¶

The most common relationships between classes are:

  1. Dependency(uses-a)
  2. Aggregation(has-a)
  3. Inheritance

In [18]:
class Dimension {
    double width;
    double height;
    
    public Dimension(double a, double b) {
        width = a;
        height = b;
    }
}
In [19]:
class Box {
    Dimension dimension;
    
    public Box(Dimension dim) {
        this.dimension = dim;
    }
}
In [21]:
Dimension dim = new Dimension(10, 10);
Box myBox = new Box(dim);

System.out.println(myBox.dimension.width);

10.0
In [ ]:
String a = new String("Hello World");
Box a = new Box(10, 20);

The dependency has-a is easy to undestand. It is concrete. For example, the class Order has a class Account because it needs to access Account object to get the information about credit status. Thus a class depends on another class if its methods use or manipulate objects of that class.
For example:

In [3]:
class Account{
    public double getCreditStatus() {
        return 2.0;
    }
}

class Order {
    Account account;
    
    public double getCreditStatus(){
       return account.getCreditStatus();
    }
    
}

The dependency uses-a is the most general and obvious relationship.For example, the Order object contains Item objects.

In [4]:
import java.util.*;

class Item {
    String name;
    Item(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
    
    public String toString() {
        return this.name;
    }
}

class Order {
    public List<Item> items = new mypackage.one.ArrayList<>();
}
In [5]:
Order order = new Order();
order.items.add(new Item("Coffee"));
Out[5]:
true
In [6]:
System.out.println(order.items)

[Coffee]

The dependency is-a expresses relationship between more general and a more special class. For example, SpecialOrder inherits from Order class and contains more attributes and methods in it.

Where storage lives¶

It’s useful to visualize the way things are laid out while the program is running—in particular, how memory is arranged. There are different places to store data:

Registers¶

This is the fastest storage because it exists in a place different from that of other storage: inside the central processing unit. However, the number of registers is severely limited, so registers are allocated as they are needed. You don’t have direct control over register allocation, nor do you see any evidence in your programs that registers even exist.

The Stack¶

This lives in the general random-access memory (RAM) area, but has direct support from the processor via its stack pointer . The stack pointer is moved down to create new memory and moved up to release that memory. This is an extremely fast and efficient way to allocate storage, second only to registers. The Java system must know, while it is creating the program, the exact lifetime of all the items stored on the stack. This constraint places limits on the flexibility of your programs, so while some Java storage exists on the stack—in particular, object references—Java objects themselves are not placed on the stack.

The heap¶

This is a general-purpose pool of memory (also in the RAM area) where all Java objects live. Unlike the stack, the compiler doesn’t need to know how long objects must stay on the heap. Thus, there’s a great deal of flexibility when using heap storage. Whenever you need an object, you write the code to create it using new , and the storage is allocated on the heap when that code is executed.

Non-RAM storage¶

If data lives completely outside a program, it can exist while the program is not running, outside the control of the program. The two primary examples of this are serialized objects , where objects are turned into streams of bytes, generally sent to another machine, and persistent objects , where the objects are placed on disk so they will hold their state even when the program is terminated.

new¶

The new operator dynamically allocates memory for an object. In the context of an assignment, it has this general form: class-var = new classname ( );

class-var - is a certain class reference variable that will refer to the created object. The classname is the name of the class that is being instantiated. The class name followed by parentheses specifies the constructor for the class. Constructors are an important part of all classes and have many significant attributes. Most real-world classes explicitly define their own constructors within their class definition. However, if no explicit constructor is specified, then Java will automatically supply a default constructor.

In [22]:
class A {
    // no constructors is explicitly specified
}
In [23]:
A a = new A(); // OK, because default constructor will be generated.

At this point, you might be wondering why you do not need to use new for such things as integers or characters. The answer is that Java’s primitive types are not implemented as objects. Later, you will see object versions of the primitive types that are available for your use in those situations in which complete objects of these types are needed.

It is important to understand that new allocates memory for an object during run time. The advantage of this approach is that your program can create as many or as few objects as it needs during the execution of your program.

Let’s once again review the distinction between a class and an object. A class creates a new data type that can be used to create objects. That is, a class creates a logical framework that defines the relationship between its members. When you declare an object of a class, you are creating an instance of that class. Thus, a class is a logical construct. An object has physical reality.

Object reference variables¶

Object reference variables act differently than you might expect when an assignment takes place. For example:

In [25]:
class AbraKadabra {
    int a = 100;
}
In [27]:
AbraKadabra abra = new AbraKadabra();
AbraKadabra kadabra = abra;
abra.a = 200;
System.out.println(abra.a);
System.out.println(kadabra.a);

200
200

After these line of code one object will be created in memory, but 2 variables "abra" and "kadabra" will be pointed on it.

But these variables are not linked together. For example:

In [30]:
kadabra = new AbraKadabra();
System.out.println(kadabra.a);
System.out.println(abra.a);

100
200

After this line these two variables will be pointed to different objects.

Constructors¶

It can be tedious to initialize all of the variables in a class each time an instance is created. It would be simpler and more concise to have all of the setup done at the time the object is first created. Because the requirement for initialization is so common, Java allows objects to initialize themselves when they are created. This automatic initialization is performed through the use of a constructor.

A constructor initializes an object immediately upon creation. It has the same name as the class in which it resides and is syntactically similar to a method. Once defined, the constructor is automatically called when the object is created, before the new operator completes.

In [25]:
class MyClass {}
MyClass myClass = new MyClass(); // default constructor will be called.

Constructors look a little strange because they have no return type, not even void. This is because the implicit return type of a class’ constructor is the class type itself. It is the constructor’s job to initialize the internal state of an object so that the code creating an instance will have a fully initialized, usable object immediately.

In [26]:
class Box {
    int width;
    int height;
    int depth;
    
    public Box() {
        System.out.println("No args constructor Box()");
        width = 10;
        height = 10;
        depth = 10;
    }
    
    public double getVolume() {
        return width * height * depth;
    }
}
In [27]:
Box box = new Box();

No args constructor Box()
In [30]:
box.height
Out[30]:
10
In [31]:
box.width
Out[31]:
10
In [32]:
box.depth
Out[32]:
10
In [33]:
box.getVolume();
Out[33]:
1000.0

As you can see, box variable was initialized by the Box() constructor when it was created. Since the constructor gives all boxes the same dimensions, 10 by 10 by 10, box will have the same volume for every object you create.

Now you can understand why the parentheses are needed after the class name. What is actually happening is that the constructor for the class is being called. The line

In [34]:
Box box = new Box();

No args constructor Box()

is calling the Box( ) constructor.|

The default constructor is often sufficient for simple classes, but it usually won’t do for more sophisticated ones. Once you define your own constructor, the default constructor is no longer used.

Caution:

Please keep in mind that you get a free no-argument constructor only when your class has no other constructors. If you write your class with even a single constructor of your own and you want the users of your class to have the ability to create an instance by a call to new ClassName() then you must provide a no-argument constructor explicitly.

Parameterized constructors¶

While the Box() constructor in the preceding example does initialize a Box object, it is not very useful—all boxes have the same dimensions. What is needed is a way to construct Box objects of various dimensions. The easy solution is to add parameters to the constructor.

In [34]:
class NewBox {

    double height;
    double width;
    double depth;
    
    public NewBox(double h, double w, double d) {
        height = h;
        width = w;
        depth = d;
    }
    
    public double getVolume() {
        return width * height * depth;
    }
    
}
In [35]:
NewBox myNewBox = new NewBox(); // will throw an exception because no default constructor was provided.

|   NewBox myNewBox = new NewBox(); // will throw an exception because no default constructor was provided.
constructor NewBox in class NewBox cannot be applied to given types;
  required: double,double,double
  found: no arguments
  reason: actual and formal argument lists differ in length
In [7]:
NewBox myNewBox = new NewBox(5, 10, 15);
In [8]:
myNewBox.getVolume();
Out[8]:
750.0

As you can see, each object is initialized as specified in the parameters to its constructor.

"this" keyword¶

Sometimes a method will need to refer to the object that invoked it. To allow this, Java defines the this keyword. This is always a reference to the object on which the method was invoked.

So, why do we need to use it? Let's consider one example:

As you know, it is illegal in Java to declare two local variables with the same name inside the same or enclosing scopes. Interestingly, you can have local variables, including formal parameters to methods, which overlap with the names of the class’ instance variables.

In [36]:
class NewBox2 {

    double height;
    double width;
    double depth;
    
    public NewBox2(double height, double width, double depth) {
        height = height;
        width = width;
        depth = depth;
    }
    
    public double getVolume() {
        return width * height * depth;
    }
    
}
In [37]:
NewBox2 nb = new NewBox2(1, 2, 3);
In [15]:
nb.getVolume();
Out[15]:
0.0

As you can see, the result of calling the method "getVolume" is 0.0 in spite of the fact that we used arguments 1, 2, 3. This happened because local veriables height, width and depth overlap the names of class' instance variables. To overcome this situation you need to use this

In [38]:
class NewBox2 {

    double height;
    double width;
    double depth;
    
    public NewBox2(double h, double w, double d) {
        height = h;
        width = w;
        depth = d;
    }
    
    public double getVolume() {
        return width * height * depth;
    }
    
}
In [39]:
NewBox2 nb = new NewBox2(1, 2, 3);
nb.getVolume();
Out[39]:
6.0

Calling another constructor¶

this keyword has a second meaning. If the first statement has the form this(...), then the constructor calls another constructor of the same class. For example:

In [43]:
public class Cat {
    int age;
    int weight;
    String name;
    
    public Cat(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        System.out.println("1 Args cons");
    }
    
    public Cat(String name, int age) {
        this(name);
        this.age = age;
        System.out.println("2 Args cons");
    }
    
    public Cat(String name, int age, int weight) {
        this(name, age);
        this.weight = weight;
        System.out.println("3 Args cons");
    }
}

|           this(name);
call to this must be first statement in constructor
In [42]:
Cat cat = new Cat("George", 10, 20);

1 Args cons
2 Args cons
3 Args cons

Using the this keyword in this manner is useful—you only need to write common construction code once.

Initialization blocks¶

You have already seen two ways to initialize a data field:
1) By setting a value in a constructor;
2) By assigning a value in the declaration.

There is a third mechanism in Java, called an initialization block.

In [ ]:
class A {
    double a = 10;
    double b = 10;
}

These blocks are executed whenever an object of that class is constructed. For example:

In [1]:
class Employee {
    public static int nextId = 0;
    private int id = 0;
    private String name = null;
    private double salary = 0.0;
    // object initialization block
    {
        System.out.println("Inside initialization block");
        id = nextId;
        nextId++;
    }
    
    public Employee(String name, double salary) {
        System.out.println("Inside Employee(String, double) constructor");
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }
    
    public Employee() {
        System.out.println("Inside empty constructor");
        this.name = "";
        this.salary = 0.0;
    }
    
    public int getId() {
        return this.id;
    }
}

In this example, the id field is initialized in the object initialization block, no matter which constructor is used to construct an object. The initialization block runs first, and then the body of the constructor is executed.

In [2]:
Employee dima = new Employee("Dima", 10000000);
System.out.println(Employee.nextId);
Employee sasha = new Employee("Sasha", 1000);
System.out.println(Employee.nextId);
System.out.println("Dima's id is " + dima.getId());
System.out.println("Sasha's id is " + sasha.getId());

Inside initialization block
Inside Employee(String, double) constructor
1
Inside initialization block
Inside Employee(String, double) constructor
2
Dima's id is 0
Sasha's id is 1

With so many ways of initializing data fields, it can be quite confusing to give all possible pathways for the construction process. Here is what happens in detail when a constructor is called:
1) If the first line of the constructor calls a second constructor,then the second constructor executes with the provided arguments.
2) Otherwise:

  a) all data are initialized to their default values(0, false, null).
  b) All field initializers and initialization blocks are executed, in the order in which they occur in the class
3) The body of constructor is executed.

static initialization block¶

If the static fields of your class require complex initialization code, use a static initialization block.

In [25]:
class Employee {

    private static int nextId;
    private int id;
    private String name;
    private double salary;
    
    // object initialization block
    {
        System.out.println("Inside initialization block");
        id = nextId;
        nextId++;
    }
    
    static {
        var generator = new Random();
        nextId = generator.nextInt(10000);
    }
    
    public Employee(String name, double salary) {
        System.out.println("Inside Employee(String, double) constructor");
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }
    
    public Employee() {
        System.out.println("Inside empty constructor");
        this.name = "";
        this.salary = 0.0;
    }
    
    public int getId() {
        return this.id;
    }
}

Static initialization occurs when the class is first loaded. Like instance fields, static fields are 0, false, or null unless you explicitly set them to another value. All static field initializers and static initialization blocks are executed in the order in which they occur in the class declaration.
